solutions.content:
Ok so for any tree, you have a root, a left sub-tree(lets call it LST) and a right sub-tree(RST). 
If I give you a BST of n-nodes and ask you to change position of any node in LST OR/AND RST, it will give rise to a new BST. So you have got a new/unique BST.
So by **Fundamental Principle Of Counting**, you need to employ multiplication b/w number of possible permutations on the left and the right.
Hence the recurrence developes:
```
T(n) = Summation(k=1 to n){T(k-1)*T(n-k)}
```
Think of it this way: If you take '**k-1**' nodes in the LST, how many nodes are left to be picked up for the RST?
'**n-k**', Right? Because 1 node has to be the root.

Following is the code snippet for it:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int rec(int n, map<int,int> &dp){
        if(n==0){
            dp[0] = 1;
            return 1;
        }
        if(dp.find(n)!=dp.end())
            return dp[n];
        int sum = 0;
        for(int k=1;k<=n;k++)
            sum += rec(n-k,dp)*rec(k-1,dp);
        dp[n] = sum;
        return sum;
    }
    int numTrees(int n) {
        map<int,int> dp;
        return rec(n,dp);
    }
};
```

Also if you want to have a mathematical formula, its the n-th Catalan Number, 
```
C(2n,n)/(n+1) where C(n,r) is the number of combinations possible for picking up r items from n unique items.
```

Happy Coding!
