# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If you carefully observe the steps involved in calculating sum of rotated array,
for ith rotation, you will notice that 
for sum calculated at rotation-(i-1) (it is called as pre), we are adding sum of array elements to it(sum) & subtracting (n*element of nums) 

(element of nums) is element from its reversed array (rev)
For rotation-1, element to be subtracted is rev[0],
for rotation-2, element to be subtracted is rev[1]
ans so on

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Let's take nums=[4,3,2,6]. So, rev=[6,2,3,4]
1. Initialize sum=15, res=25(for rotation-0), pre=25 (pre is sum of previous rotated array)
2. For 1st rotaion: temp = pre+sum-(4*6) = 25+15-24 = 16. 
   pre becomes 16
3. For 2nd rotation: temp = pre+sum-(4*2) = 16+15-8 = 23.             
   Update res=23
   pre=23
4. For 3rd rotation: temp=pre+sum-(4*3) = 23+15-12 = 26.          
   Update res=26
5. Keep doing this, till rotation<=(n-1)
6. At the end, return res

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n) for storing reverse of array nums

