# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
My intuition on this problem is that we would need to first subtract n - 1 (n = nums.size) times the last number, and add the first number from f(k - 1) (which is the one timed by zero in the equations) and then add the rotation sum between the first number and the last 
number non-inclusive to get f(k). 
first solution:
    - uses a sliding window to calculate the sum between the ranges before hand and save it in a vector
    -  calculates the actual sum
    -  loop through nums again starting from index 1 
    -  do the above calculation while updating first number 
    -  and store the max in a integer and returns it

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Then I started coding it, and the complexity has a large constant but my accepted time is still below 200ms. However I know this isn't the best solution, we should be able to lower the constant.
Then I realised that, if we are adding the sum of all elements in nums instead of just the range, then you would only need to subtract n * current last number from f(k) to get the rotation sum
therefore, the new approach would be
    - loop through nums to calculate the sum and the rotation sum f(0)
    - loop through nums again from index 1
    - increment the current rotation sum by the sum of all numbers, and minus the current rotation sum by the last number of f(k) times n
    - saves the max value and in the end, return it


# Complexity
Overall time complexity T(N) = 4N since we are looping through the array twice and both loops has 2 constant operations.

and since we are not using any data structure to store any elements, space should be constant.

therefore: 
Time complexty: 

- Time complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
- Space complexity: O(1)
